HEADWORD: Bier
<hw>Bier</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>b⟦ae⟧e</ets>,
<ets>beere</ets>, AS. <ets>b⟦aemac⟧r</ets>, <ets>b⟦aemac⟧re</ets>; akin
to D. <ets>baar</ets>, OHG. <ets>b⟦amac⟧ra</ets>, G. <ets>bahre</ets>,
Icel <ets>barar</ets>, Dutch <ets>baare</ets>, L. <ets>feretrum</ets>,
Gr. <ets><?/</ets>, from the same <?/<?/ <ets>bear</ets> to produce. See
1st <er>Bear</er>, and cf. <er>Barrow</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
handbarrow or portable frame on which a corpse is placed or borne to the
grave.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Weaving)</fld> <def>A count of forty threads in the
warp or chain of woolen cloth.</def> <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

